Exercise 3

fisheries <- read_csv("data/fisheries.csv")
## Rows: 216 Columns: 4
## â”€â”€ Column specification â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (1): country
## dbl (3): capture, aquaculture, total
## 
## â„¹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
## â„¹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
fisheries_new <- fisheries %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = -country, names_to = "Harvest") %>%
  filter(Harvest %in% c("capture", "aquaculture")) %>%
  mutate(value = as.numeric(value))
fisheries_new
## # A tibble: 432 Ã— 3
##    country        Harvest     value
##    <chr>          <chr>       <dbl>
##  1 Afghanistan    capture      1000
##  2 Afghanistan    aquaculture  1200
##  3 Albania        capture      7886
##  4 Albania        aquaculture   950
##  5 Algeria        capture     95000
##  6 Algeria        aquaculture  1361
##  7 American Samoa capture      3047
##  8 American Samoa aquaculture    20
##  9 Andorra        capture         0
## 10 Andorra        aquaculture     0
## # â€¦ with 422 more rows
fisheries_new <- fisheries_new %>%
  filter(country %in% c("China", "Russia", "Norway", "Malaysia", "Spain", "Nigeria", "France", "Mauritania", "Ghana", "Mozambique", "Poland", "Sierra Leone", "Laos", "Panama", "Seychelles", "Saudi Arabia"))
fisheries_new %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(fill = Harvest, y=value, x=country)) + geom_bar(position="stack", stat="identity") + scale_y_log10()
## Warning: Transformation introduced infinite values in continuous y-axis
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing missing values (geom_bar).

I created a new variable, harvest, putting both aquaculture and capture in it so I could create a stacked bar chart. I then log scaled the y axis so you could see more. I then kept only the countries with the most, the ones that were in the chart provided. This made it look much better. I could also adjust the x axis to make it easier to read.

Exerciser 4

library(tidyverse) 
library(mosaicData) 
?Whickham

This is likely observational data since it is a survey.

nrow(Whickham)
## [1] 1314
ncol(Whickham)
## [1] 3

1314 observations, each is a person. 3 variables, representing if they are alive/dead, smoker or not, and age. I would expect the smokers to be more likely to be less healthy.

Whickham %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(fill = outcome, x=smoker)) + geom_bar()

Whickham %>%
  count(smoker, outcome)
##   smoker outcome   n
## 1     No   Alive 502
## 2     No    Dead 230
## 3    Yes   Alive 443
## 4    Yes    Dead 139

68.6% of Non smokers are alive 76% of smokers are alive

Whickham <- Whickham %>%
  mutate(age_cat = case_when(
    age <= 44 ~ "18-44",
    age > 44 & age <= 64 ~ "45-64",
    age > 64 ~ "65+"
))
Whickham %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(fill = outcome, x=smoker)) + facet_wrap(~age_cat)+geom_bar() 

Whickham %>%
  count(smoker, age_cat, outcome)
##    smoker age_cat outcome   n
## 1      No   18-44   Alive 327
## 2      No   18-44    Dead  12
## 3      No   45-64   Alive 147
## 4      No   45-64    Dead  53
## 5      No     65+   Alive  28
## 6      No     65+    Dead 165
## 7     Yes   18-44   Alive 270
## 8     Yes   18-44    Dead  15
## 9     Yes   45-64   Alive 167
## 10    Yes   45-64    Dead  80
## 11    Yes     65+   Alive   6
## 12    Yes     65+    Dead  44

You can see that at a young age, smoking doesnt imapct health status. In middle age, the smokers start to die more, and in old age is where smoking really shows its head.
